In article <332ah1$nvv@triode.apana.org.au>, cskinner@triode.apana.org.au (Christopher T Skinner) writes:
> I have been told that DES is in the public domain only for "Banking"
> and "Key" encryption. ie it is Not public domain for any old data.
> Is this so? If so does this restriction have any meaning?
> Is a "Key" data?
> If I put some money in my message is that "Banking"?
> cts NSW

DES was patented; however, IBM granted a free license to anyone who
used the standard modes.  The question is moot now, because the patent
has already expired.
